Interview: Digital Radio Politics: Tech cultural and engineering challenges in campaigns

http://radioactivebroadcasting.net/directory/item/952-open-standards-strengthen-political-industry

Last week, after Campaign Tech West, I joined Karen Jagoda, President of the E-Voting institute and host of Digital Politics Radio (Podcast) for a interview.
If you tend to be more oral and aural, this is better than a blog post  

The interview has to ~10min segments. Check them out here:
Or go directly to the audio file @ Digital Politics Radio site

We discussed many of the cultural and engineering challenges campaigns and non-profits face when applying technical assets and resources to their goals.
In the interview, you’ll hear me run my mouth about:
	What does “Tech” mean? What’s the difference between Digital and Tech?
	What is the current tech, or engineering talent landscape look like?
	As technical resources and assets have rapidly shifted from ancillary to strategic, what challenges exist within campaigns and their internal departments that limit us and what an approach to overcoming them can look like.
	What engineering and integration problems are limiting us and what is an approach to overcoming them?
	What’s the history and cause of the formation of the Open Supporter Data Interface (OSDI)?
	 The cleanliness state of multiple siloed datasets in organizations.

message:
Oh HeartBleed.  Had you been a vulnerability in SChannel, Windows SSL stack, we'd never hear the end of the recriminations of Microsoft incompetence and how proprietary closed-source is said to fail in just this way.  Open Source ensures that a gazillion eyes see the code and these nasty problems get fixed.  NOT!

This wasn't even a complicated bug.  Letting the incoming payload (controlled by the attacker) determine the bounds of a memory allocation, and then not scrubbing the memory..  

These are the kinds of things that proprietary shops like Google and Microsoft employ processes to weed out.
What kind of fuzzy analyzers are the OSS community running against critical codebases like this?

https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/96db9023b881d7cd9f379b0c154650d6c108e9a3#diff-38dc72994741420e2b6c5ee074941a45R1498
name: openssl/openssl
caption: github.com
description: Contribute to openssl development by creating an account on GitHub.

data.message: Agreed. However, "It's amazing that entire internet, including big companies like Google and Facebook rely on this tiny OpenSSL foundation, which manages the free encryption library. They have four developers working on the project, and only one full time. Maybe these multi-billion dollar companies could throw in some money to help preserve the future of the internet. As cryptographer Matthew Green told the New York Times, 'If we could get $500,000 kicked back to OpenSSL and teams like it, maybe this kind of thing won't happen again."" --  http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/apr/12/silicon-valley-nsa-reform-taking-so-long?CMP=twt_gu

"What happened was that over two years ago a volunteer—one who isn't even a member of the OpenSSL project—submitted a line of code with an error in it that was not caught during review and was eventually implemented."

message: Throwback Nerdsday+1   OG Mozilla & Netscape Proxy Server product box.  I was a developer on this product in 1996-1997.  Note the system requirements label.  Solaris SPARC, IBM AIX, DEC Alpha, SGI MIPS, IRIX, HPUX,

data.message: No Linux yet!

That's right.  I honestly can't remember the details, but I'm guessing that NSPR (the netscape portability layer) had not yet been ported to it.   It wasn't really supported on Solaris X86 either, but I made it run on my home machine.  My work machine was a Sun Ultra, but by home machine was Solaris X86.  On an ISDN connection into netscape.
Vinod Valloppillil Our box was much cooler!
whaaa???  ;)

Steve Rubio Proxy servers are similar to web server (often using  the same code, but running in different modes).  They are often used at work as part of the firewall between the corporate network and the Internet.  If you've ever seen "Proxy Settings" or "Automatically detect my proxy settings" that is what the browser is talking about.
Likely at the time we had an nspr for Linux but the quality of it plus the compilers (aka gcc) wasn't good enough.

Vinod Valloppillil Remember caching protocols?  We/NSCP wanted to do http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_Cache_Protocol
MSFT wanted to do some hashing thing.  What was it called? CRAP?

heh.. 'CARP' - but yep, not exactly the best marketing / naming decision ever  ;-)   FWIW, some of the core ideas in CARP were later developed - totally in parallel - into this http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consistent_hashing
Familiar props!  The green Mozilla now lives in the menagerie of my kids' stuffed animals and I continue to use the Proxy Server box as a monitor stand.
Alexander Feygin Thats a good use for it! I need to put the server administration manual back inside to make it stiff enough.

Randall Gellens  yes, but that is a huge hassle.  If you are dealing with tens of thousands of records (say voter lists) ZIP codes are often a problem.
I blame the US govt and Obama, there should be no zipcodes with leading zeroes.

Peter S. Ford Typical Microsoft thinking,

and I thought I was being a clever Internet conspiracy theorist ...

Of course Excel has it:

1. Select the cells which will contain zip codes.
2. Right-click and select "Format Cells...."
3. Click on the "Number" tab.
4. Select "Special" in the type box.
5. Select "Zip Code" or "Zip Code +4," as necessary

There are also pre-defined formats available for phone numbers and Social Security numbers.

Response to petition: RTFM.

Josh, why is the number of records an issue?  Can you do a select column or something?  Perhaps the files are being created by tools (not manually) and hence changing the format would be a big hassle?  If so, you can edit the raw XML with your own scripts/tools.  (I got really fed up that Excel lacked the ability to do a find/replace using regular expressions, so I wrote a Perl script that did it to the raw XML.)
If the spreadsheets need to be created without manual intervention, then a script to change the formatting could be part of that process.  A hassle, sure.

Given that the vast majority of people don't care about preserving leading zeros, and that there is a way to format columns to preserve data with leading zeros, this sounds like a reasonable design decision. http://office.microsoft.com/en-us/excel-help/keep-leading-zeros-in-number-codes-HA010342581.aspx

message:
I'm really liking my Dell Venue 8 Pro windows tablet.  In the 2 weeks I've had it, I haven't wanted to touch my iPad.  SO much more productive.  and I don't just mean Office.

The Metro apps are pretty sweet.  Most of the big ones I need are there, plus some other neat things.  
With real Windows, if there isn't a metro app (or more likely, I want to do something unusual), I can just swipe windows to get to the desktop and run a real app.

It's nice to have a REAL filesystem.  I can work real files.  I have git repositories local.  I don't have to fight with prickly iOS apps, their Dropbox et al file support, making voodoo  "Open in XYZ app" to edit anything.  IMHO that almost NEVER works.

For those moments walking around "Oooh I should add this little feature, or I know how to fix that bug!"

Ruby on Rails is installed, RubyMine IDE.  

I even  can run the actual Rails server and test  browse to it from my iPhone at the coffee shop.

The Dell fits in my coat pocket (8", those areal inches not AOL inches).  I've even got some tiny and small Bluetooth/keyboard pointer combos.  Love the Lenovo mobile Bluetooth and TrackPoint combo!

Split Screen is super cool too!.  Want to view a link a friend sent in email?  no prob. Clicking it splits the screen between mail and browser.  I can see and work with both at the same time.  When I'm done just swipe to disappear the browser. Same thing in many apps.

 No more double click the iOS home button, then click the mail or source  app to go back to the email.  

Of course, Apple Fanboys can relax.  It is not as perfect as your precious iDevices.

UPDATE:  Paul Johns pointed out that you can close metro apps by swiping from top to bottom and holding.  Nice.
Apple Fanboys - Go pound sand.

HOWEVER.  I really hate when developers try to be *too clever*  PLEASE Microsoft, make a close button/swipe/other mechanism to easily CLOSE an application manually..   Yes the app linger algorithm is very clever and works most of the time.  But that depends on everything working right.  

Not every 3rd party metro  app is perfect and sometimes they crash or get into a wacky state you can't fix without killing the process.
If I could just swipe/select an app in the left vertical app list and then click "Exit" life would be so much simpler.

An escape hatch like a close mechanism would really help.

Since I don't have that, whenever an app goes bad, I have to drop down to desktop mode, launch the task manager and end process.  

Am I missing a close function somewhere?

data.message: I feel the same way, but I decided the Dell 8" wasn't big enough for the traditional Win apps for me. Switched to a Surface Pro + the click keyboard (whatever it's called) (much bigger investment, but totally replaced my personal laptop) & I"m super happy.
Wow, that must be SpikedCoolAid 2.0 kicking in.   ;)

You close a modern UI app by swiping from the top to bottom. It's one of my favorite gestures, actually....so dramatic! :)

Glad you're enjoying the tablet. I've had my Lenovo Thinkpad 2 for a year now, and I prefer it to any hardware I have (except when speed is an issue). Your tablet has a CPU about twice as fast AND faster memory AND MUCH faster graphics, so those might not be an issue for you.....

Are there any web sites that are so "busy" that browsing them is slow? I have problems with sites that have a lot of motion ads and slideshows.

Nevin Williams  No Kool Aid here.  I've been gone from Microsoft for almost 1.5 years.  They said the implant should stop working well before that.

Amy Blumenfield  I hear you.  I got the Dell Venue as a cheap way to get into Windows Tablet.  32GB=$250, 64G=$319.

It is quite small and the newer displays dont seem to like DPI scaling very well.  It isn't so much the resolution, it's the DPI.  Text can be small to read.

I'm also eyeing a Surface Pro, but also the Lenovo Mix 2 10"  It's a nice detachable tablet keyboard combo with pointing device.
http://shop.lenovo.com/us/en/tablets/ideatab/miix-series/miix-2-10-inch/

Paul Johns I looked at the Tablet 2, but I'd wait for a refresh on it component-wise.  However, the keyboard I am using is the one for the tablet 2. (See my pics!)

Microsoft has done a really good job on the tablet (modern UI) side of Windows 8.1--it's elegant, and quite well-designed.

When I bought my tablet a year ago, they were SERIOUSLY behind on modern UI apps; now it's not so bad, at least for major apps. And being able to run legacy Windows apps--not to mention Office--as well really rocks, as does Windows Update, which fixes problems far quicker than waiting for an update for the entire OS (major advantage, actually).

I wish Microsoft would include pinch-to-zoom for the desktop (perhaps with an even simpler gesture to activate it) to allow you to make areas of the screen with small items to touch larger.

Paul Johns I was able to increase the size of items on my screen.  The UI will tell you that you can't.  But if you click the "one size for all of my displays" (and be sure to turn off syncing those settings to your other devices) then you can change the DPI setting.
I wouldn't buy a TPT2 now either, but they are/were $369 at Egghead, so looks like Lenovo is starting to clear them out.....
That's not good enough--I don't want everything bigger all the time, only when I want to touch them. The rest of the time they're a good size.
Well there is the ease of access magnifier...
Yup... that almost does it, but not easy enough to use for this purpose. Compare w/ Chrome on Android which zooms automatically if it can't resolve the touch.
If Microsoft chose to seriously think about the problem "How can we make the desktop work as well as possible with touch?" they'd make some progress....

I'm in CA SCM land now.  Wow.
Since each git is its own repository, if you clone something into multiple places and aren't rigorous about merging them back into a central repository, they're basically going to fork.

Chris Wright: count me in that tally. I have used both Perforce and Git (and SCCS, yes SCCS, RCS, CVS and Subversion) and I find Perforce infinitely easier to use than Git. This is the point where someone will point out all the magical things Git can do that Perforce cannot (and that's definitely not an empty set) but I have learnt to follow Zed Shaw's advise: https://twitter.com/zedshaw/status/64883570388373504 :-). So instead of arguing the merits and demerits, I like to say that Perforce is better than Git for fools, and there are more fools (like me) in the world than the smart people who *need* to understand what a "detached head" is to use a VCS.

Bob.   I disagree.    I watched this on the Rachel Maddow show and he lifted verbatim, word for word, ideas about 2 movies and the exact comparisons that were made on Wikipedia. message: Why do older people become republicans?

data.message: Because they're sick and tired of those damn democrats!

I heard a recent stat that in the state of MA, if you get on every assistance program that the state has to offer, it is the equivalent of earning a 54K/year salary.  That's where my tax dollars are going.
Their parents don't love them.
My Dad always said we'd become Republicans when we got older and had money. Not that I have that much money, but still hasn't happened yet. Poor guy had three sons, not a Republican in the bunch.
They don't...at least not in my case nor the cases of almost everyone else I know who would fit into the "older" category.
It's the old saying, if you're young and you're not a Democrat you have no heart.  If you're old and you're not a Republican you have no brain.
Because young people cause all the problems
I read government budget and saw that in 2012, 19 percent, or $689 billion when into the military budget. That's where MY tax dollars are going. :-(
Because once they get their "Socialist" Medicare and Social Security they become greedy and don't want anyone else to get it! ;)
When I was in my 20's I was a Republican. Now that I am older, and not nearly as ignorant as I was back then, I am a Democrat.
I mostly blame parenthood. It does weird things to a lot of people.
@Fabio: I don't know how anyone with a brain can be a Republican nowadays, regardless of age.
the AARP discounted Early Bird membership?
The AARP is pretty liberal especially by today's standards.

“Show me a young Conservative and I'll show you someone with no heart. Show me an old Liberal and I'll show you someone with no brains.”

― Winston Churchill

The reality of the Dems and Republicans in the U.S. is that they are two faces on the same coin.  Both "sides" voted for the Iraq war, the Patriot act, the revocation of Glass-Steagal, the lack of regulation on derivatives trading, and most of the bad budget management in the Federal Govt.    The tragedy in the US is that the Fed govt is ruled by the two parties while a solid third of the population identifies itself as independent.
I started out libertarian (foolish youth!) and moved steadily left over the years.
It appears that that quote and similar ones are falsely attributed to Churchill by some cowardly scoundrel wanting to steal Churchill's authority for their (rather nasty) idea.

Peter, which the two parties do indeed have the things you mention in common, it is simply false to say that they're "two sides of the same coin" because of their many--and significant--differences. If they were both the same, there would be no need for the Republicans to blockade Congress.

The problem with the false meme that the parties are the same is that it plays into the hands of the conservatives by promoting the hatred of government they need to thrive. If it were true, that would be one thing. But it's not.

But to Peter's point, look at the current situation--the Dems are suddenly the can't-get-to-war-fast-enough hawks and the Republicans are in places balking at a military strike. I'm absolutely amazed at the place we find ourselves. Mostly, it just proves that pure politics trump any sort of principles or beliefs in D.C.
Oh, and the answer I think to your original question is money. I certainly care more and more about keeping mine for myself and my family as I get older. :-)

It is true that as you get older you get more insecure which leads to a person becoming greedier as heather pointed out. But I think with age as the body and mind start to deteriorate in many they can't learn new things as they did in the past and distrust the younger generations and become more conservative as a way of clinging on to the past. There is a reason you don't see many 80 year olds heading back to school to further their education.

I think people tend to become more "conservative" (opposed to change) as they age because it literally becomes harder for them to adjust.  Young minds can learn quickly and adjust to new environments.  As people age, their brains tend to slow down and are not able to adjust nearly as quickly to new knowledge or situations.

I would love to see a clear 3 areas where the 2 parties are significantly different, along with evidence that the members actually believe what the party proposes, and that they actually get results along those lines.   For example, the republicans believe in smaller government, yet since Reagan's time they don't vote for smaller government, and the budget keeps climbing - GONG!   The democrats claim they want regulation of the banks, but major bank deregulation that led to disaster occurred under the direction of the goldman sachs kids who worked in the Clinton Administration - GONG!

Peter is using texas sharpshooter reasoning.  
You picked data to suit your argument, or found a pattern to fit a presumption.
This 'false cause' fallacy is coined after a marksman shooting randomly at barns and then painting bullseye targets around the spot where the most bullet holes appear, making it appear as if he's a really good shot. Clusters naturally appear by chance, but don't necessarily indicate that there is a causal relationship.

name: NYT: Greenwald's Partner Was Transporting Snowden's Stolen Documents
caption: littlegreenfootballs.com
description: The New York Times report on today's huge libertarian freak-out has a very interesting detail, completely left out of the reports by the Guardian and Glenn Greenwald: Britain Detains the Partner of a Reporter Tied to Leaks. Mr. Miranda was in Berlin to deliver documents related to Mr. Greenwald's in...

data.message: "Mr. Miranda, Mr. Greenwald said, was told that he was being detained under Section 7 of the British Terrorism Act, which allows the authorities to detain someone for up to nine hours for questioning and to conduct a search of personal items, often without a lawyer, to determine possible ties to terrorism." I mean, is anyone outside the hysterical short-circuitings of the right blogosphere really making the case that what the Greenwald underground has been up to constitutes, you know, terrorism?

Thats a fair question and with the obvious caveat of us not knowing all of the details I'll say this.  If these guys are running around with *stolen*, *classified* information about how a government's security and antiterrorism mechanisms work, then it's not unreasonable to try to catch them and take it away from them.

No doubt on the face of it it's a reasonable thing for a government to do; whether it's a legal or even prudent thing for a government to do with a fairly carefully written anti-terror statue is another thing. If it came out tomorrow that David Miranda was patsying ten pounds of yellow cake for the Syrian resistance I think American liberals would sleep well at night; for now it looks like the transantlantic security state is using East German theories of jurisprudence to deprive a Brazilian twink of his Nintendo. More to come, certainly.

message: Watched this documentary about Wikileaks saga with Josh Cohen last night. I found it to be very "balanced." Which I mean not in the horrible 24 hour news cycle way of everyone with an opinion speaks, but in a though-provoking way. Made me consider there is a lot of demonizing and lionizing going on from both sides of the authoritarian/transparency debate. It's viewed as a great showdown between Asange and Obama, who are merely symbols of political thought. Ultimately, I walked away thinking neither man was a saintly as their supporters think, nor as evil as the detractors say.

message: Why does Outlook 2013 IMAP suck when using gmail?  Anyone figured out how to make Drafts work correctly?

data.message: Gmail IMAP is an abomination. Because of the label business. Made worse by the fact that their SMTP server saves outgoing mail to the Sent folder.
Ahhh.  thats why I see 2 copies of my messages in my sent folder.

but I can't ignore the fact that the Drafts problem did not occur in Outlook 2010.  I'm surprised they didn't fully test gmail/outlook.  gmail is so popular and the poor support steers people away from outlook and towards gmail's web interface.

On my Mac, Drafts never worked well because Apple Mail was saving the draft every few seconds and Gmail was making multiple copies of it at their end... one day upon checking the Drafts folder using the Gmail web interface I found thousands of messages with 10s of copies of each message! I ranted at length here: http://code.ahren.org/bit/life-with-gmails-broken-imap, but please don't bother reading it, it just makes me sad. I was self-hoted for years and years but ultimately all the SPF and other spam filtering and black/whitelisting became a pain and I moved to Gmail. After these travails, I switched out of Gmail 2-3 years ago to iCloud. Can't do multiple identities etc, but it works predictably.
But yeah if it worked in Outlook 2010, MS must have put in some workarounds for Gmail weirdness that did carry over to the newer version.
What? This is the kind of shit people go to you for!
Why are you using Outlook?

name: Adria Richards, PyCon, and How We All Lost
caption: amandablumwords.wordpress.com
description: Adria Richards was an attendee at PyCon, a tech conference, as part of her job as a developer evangelist at Sendgrid, a tech company that manages emails.    She took offense to a conversation two m...

data.message: Marc Love

Great post on the situation. Yes, she could have handled the situation better. But what happened afterwards so outweighs the original offense that I consider it relatively minor in the whole story. It was absurd that Play Haven fired the guy, incredibly disturbing that Adria was subjected to death & rape threats (with a largely "well what did she expect" attitude from other developers), and outrageous that she lost her job as a result. The whole thing really makes me sick to my stomach.
Seems to me that at every step of the way, people opted for extreme measures rather than reasonable behavior. There they go again, those human beings always causing trouble

I do have to say though, that the point when things went off the rails when Adria chose to publicly post the picture rather than handle the situation privately.  Once that happened, there was really no turning back.  The guys shouldnt have said what they said, but at least the one guy was classy about it and apologized.  People are going to make mistakes and that is just reality.  What's more important to me is that when mistakes are brought to someone's attention that they apologize, and/or make amends.  If they don't then they may face consequences.  However, if you don't give someone a chance to make those amends, then there is no opportunity to learn.
For a second, I thought you were talking about the Cylon attack on Picon. Oops.

story: Josh Cohen shared NYC Black Pride's photo.
name: Timeline Photos
caption:
Black Pride honors Black History Month...
We remember Frederick Douglass on this day, February 14th, the date he chose to celebrate his birthday. As like most African Americans born before or during slavery, the exact date and the exact year of Douglass' birth is unknown (on the first page of "Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave", he stated: "I have no accurate knowledge of my age, never having seen any authentic record containing it."). He was an African American social reformer, orator, writer and statesman. After escaping from slavery, he became a leader of the abolitionist movement, gaining note for his dazzling oratory and incisive antislavery writing. He stood as a living counter-example to slaveholders' arguments that slaves did not have the intellectual capacity to function as independent American citizens. Douglass wrote several autobiographies, eloquently describing his experiences in slavery. His first was his 1845 autobiography, "Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave", which became influential in its support for abolition. He wrote two more autobiographies, with his last, "Life and Times of Frederick Douglass", published in 1881 and covering events through and after the Civil War. After the Civil War, Douglass remained active in the United States' struggle to reach its potential as a "land of the free". He also actively supported women's suffrage. Without his approval, he became the first African American nominated for Vice President of the United States as the running mate of Victoria Woodhull on the impracticable and small Equal Rights Party ticket. He held multiple public offices and was a firm believer in the equality of all people, whether black, female, Native American, or recent immigrant. He was famously quoted as saying, "I would unite with anybody to do right and with nobody to do wrong." Douglass also produced several abolitionist newspapers: "The North Star", "Frederick Douglass Weekly", "Frederick Douglass' Paper," "Douglass' Monthly" and "New National Era". The motto of "The North Star" was "Right is of no Sex – Truth is of no Color – God is the Father of us all, and we are all brethren." The abolitionist newspapers were mainly funded by supporters in England, who had sent him five hundred pounds to use as he chose. In 1848, Douglass was the only African American to attend the first women's rights convention, the Seneca Falls Convention. Elizabeth Cady Stanton asked the assembly to pass a resolution asking for women's suffrage. Douglass stood and spoke eloquently in favor stating that "he could not accept the right to vote as a black man if women could not also claim that right". He also suggested that the world would be a better place if women were involved in the political sphere. By the time of the Civil War, Douglass was one of the most famous black men in the country. He and other abolitionists argued that because the aim of the Civil War was to end slavery, African Americans should be allowed to engage in the fight for their freedom. President Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation, which took effect on January 1, 1863, declared the freedom of all slaves in Confederate-held territory. Douglass conferred with President Abraham Lincoln in 1863 on the treatment of black soldiers, and with President Andrew Johnson on the subject of black suffrage. During the U.S. Presidential Election of 1864, Douglass supported John C. Frémont. He was disappointed that President Lincoln did not publicly endorse suffrage for black freedmen. Douglass believed that since African American men were fighting in the American Civil War, they deserved the right to vote. In 1877, Douglass was appointed a United States Marshal. In 1881, he was appointed Recorder of Deeds for the District of Columbia. He was appointed minister-resident and consul-general to the Republic of Haiti (1889–1891). In 1892, the Haitian government appointed Douglass as its commissioner to the Chicago World's Columbian Exposition. Also in 1892, Douglass constructed rental housing for blacks, now known as Douglass Place, in the Fells Point area of Baltimore. The complex was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2003. We shall never forget...

message: it's great to see all the interest in gun control after the recent tragedies.  However, why hasn't there been more attention to mental illness?  Though guns may be a force multiplier that increases the damage, why aren't we implementing better mental health care so we can spot and stop people before they hurt others or themselves?

data.message: I'm pretty sure the conservative coalition doesn't want to pay for it
perhaps if they looked more deeply at the situation, saw the connections, they might see it as a way to keep more gun rights they might pay for it.
This is a key part of so many problems in our nation. Tipper Gore was way ahead of our time when she was working to end stigma attached to mental illness.
http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/18/health/a-misguided-focus-on-mental-illness-in-gun-control-debate.html?ref=science&_r=0

Agree, and it isn't just mental health. It is addressing the societal issues that cause gun violence. Some of that can be contributed to availability of guns, mental health, and many other factors. Guns are the red herring IMHO.
Lane Hudson agree.  As a community that often suffers a great deal of inflicted illness due to bullying and other behaviors, our own community can do much more

Julie Goldberg On a broad level, that study may be true.  However, when you look at the list of tragedies being recited now (columbine etc) mental illness is cited as a factor.  The combination of illness, ostracizing, bullying or other negative societal behaviors, and the availability of firepower is a set up for these situations.

I agree.  And I do think we need to remove the stigma of dealing with mental illness and get it covered.  I also liked the piece "I am Adam Lanza's Mother" that was making the rounds this weekend.  That said, to reduce mass killings or simply to reduce violence in this country, we need more effective gun control laws (and a cultural change that doesn't glorify violence).  You already get less gun violence in states with more restrictive laws.  I may not want to go hunting, but I'm not going to take away someone's hunting rifle, so long as they're trained in gun safety.  But you don't need a semi-automatic weapon to hunt deer.  And the background checks people go through to buy a gun from a dealer also need to be done at gun shows.

Julie Goldberg Yup.  Both issues (among others) are at play.  It's inappropriate to argue that we need to focus on mental illness or other contributing factors *instead* of gun control laws.  It's equally inappropriate to do vice versa.  My frustration is seeing the seemingly never ending stream of posts, emails and petitions that focus on one issue.
I totally agree that we need to work on BOTH, as well as changing our violent culture.
http://www.sfgate.com/opinion/openforum/article/I-am-Adam-Lanza-s-mother-4125542.php

You don't hear about mass-shootings at banks, outside airports, or near government buildings. Schools should have security or some of the teachers armed and trained. It takes the police 20 minutes to arrive at a scene. We should change the gun laws, but that won't make schools any safer.

R74: we now have a 6.3 point lead.  W00t.  blowout?

data.message:
....and 93,000 King County votes still to be counted.....

Not a blowout, but solid--and far better than I was expecting and will be better than R-71. Excellent!
Luv this! Makes me feel so wonderful for everyones work on the campaign! woohoo
Wow. That rocks.
How can they still be counting?  Do you guys vote with colored pebbles?  No, wait.  They would have finished toting up those days ago.

People can only verify signatures at a certain rate. The counting machines only run at a certain rate. Ballots will arrive in the mail after election day.

You can add more people and more machines, but at some point you get diminishing returns for something that doesn't really matter that much.

Most of the counties in the state have ballots outstanding still: http://vote.wa.gov/results/current/Turnout.html
I don't understand the counties that have one or three remainder votes left to be counted and they won't be counted until the 27th.
The networks may need a third category:  Red states, Blue states, sane states.

Dustin: I don't know why--perhaps given that there's such a small number they delay counting provisional ballots until just before the deadline to allow others to arrive.

Bob: Our election system is the best in the country. All balloting is handled by mail; ballots are easy to fill in and are easily read by both humans and machines, and we have a paper trail, so we can do recounts to eliminate errors. And the results are available in plenty of time for laws to take effect and for transitions from one official to another.

What's insane is to have people vote with electronic machines that create no paper trail, meaning there's no way to count the ballots if there's an issue, and no way to fix problems if the system is hacked. THAT'S insane.

data.message: Entrapment is only when they get someone to do something he isn't otherwise inclined to do.   Getting a drug dealer to sell more drugs isn't entrapment.  Talking someone who had never planned on selling drugs into making his first sale is.

There were prior texts with the suspect in illegal behavior.  It's just like a prostitute sting operation. No one is saying you have to answer a text, a phone call, or stop to see how much a person is charging for sex or to do anything illegal. If you do, you might just get arrested.

data.message:
You know, I get tired of these type of attacks on occupiers. The munging of multiple logical fallacies and the utter lack of understanding of the occupy argument makes this a useless comparison.

The occupy movement isn't about outlawing corporations or their products, it's about the undue influence they have over our economy and particularly our government. What the anarchist/occupier is wearing is completely irrelevant to the discussion.

Besides, in a world dominated by multi-national corporations and the inability/impracticality of making your own clothes and shoes, what the hell else are they going to wear?
You're making the association between these anarchist/thugs and the occupy folks. I dpm
I don't think that they are one & the same.

that image is an attack on a Black Bloc anarchist, who probably has a BofA checking account as well.  Are you saying anarchists and occupiers are one and the same?  Either way, hypocrisy is completely relevant in this debate.

Maybe they're not occupiers, and just anarchists, but the critique remains the same. It's a totally irrelevant way of dismissing any legitimate issues these folks might have. It's been used against the occupiers as well.

you know what another irrelevant way of dismissing their issues is?  property destruction.  It's not just big corporate buildings, either.  Ask the cupcake shop and car owners in the Mission down in SF.

I don't condone the destruction of anyone's property. I agree with you, it makes it hard to take their issues seriously. Still, two wrongs don't make a right and this image demonstrates a complete lack of understanding of the underlying issues.
Enlighten me: what is the underlying issue that results in taking a garbage can lid to a plate glass window that is not being understood here?

Enlighten me: Do you really think they're doing it for sport? Come on. I don't know what their issue is - I misidentified them as occupiers. But every protest action - whether it's peaceful or ends in violence or property destruction - has an underlying issue. If you cannot recognize that fact, I don't know how or why we can would continue this conversation.

I can't be against the insane profits of Starbucks on my way to pick up a Venti Latte.  Pointing out that kind of hypocrisy is not only fair game, it's insanely appropriate, maybe even educational.  You should look into what anarchists really want, what their "issue" is.  But, since you've both drawn offense at people misunderstanding the underlying issue, then admitted you don't know what the underlying issue is yourself, perhaps we are done here sir.

Oh come on! This was just getting good guys.  A number of these anarchists did their damage, and then took off their black clothing revealing normal clothing and then blended into the crowd.  I saw a video of one of them doing it right in front of a news crew!  I can't decide if that was ballsy or cowardly.

ballsy. Wearing the clothing of whom they hate is just part of the madness of society. Im sure they would be glad to make their own clothes. When you have no choice you do things that dont necessarily sacrfice your values. It may look to you as hypocrytical. Ive been homeless and starving, down to 110 pounds and you take what food you can get even if its from whom you despise. ITS CALLED SURVIVAL. Ive gotten a North Face jacket,  LL Bean pants  and much more from the salvation army. Maybe you folks will learn something from my comment.

data.message: I had the dubious pleasure of owning the ADSI and WMI providers for IIS for about a year after IIS 6 shipped, around 2003-4. The code in the ADSI provider was sloppy, but quite comprehensible. The WMI provider came from the SMS team, I think. The code was cleaner, but I never succeeded in wrapping my head around the insanely complex model. I was very, very glad to leave the WMI provider behind when I left Microsoft.

History Lesson:  Etymology of ginker
A low life burn out. Normally seen driving an old Camaro/Firebird covered in primer spots and Led Zepplin booming from the stereo. A chain wallet and a jean jacket is always part of the ginker look. This term may have originated in East Brunswick New Jersey in the 70s.

Allegedly: “Ginker” first appeared in English in the early 1970s as “Gink” referring to any member of the Ginkovitz family of East Brunswick, NJ and later the term evolved to its present form of “Ginker”.

Sometimes it makes sense just do it the way unix does it.

data.message: Take an architecture tour, if you can. If you can't, take a walking tour, and be sure to walk by the Carson Pirie Scott building (now a different department store) and also Marina City. Take the elevator to the top of Willis Tower (f/k/a Sears Tower) if you can. Chicago's a fascinating city for architecture, arguably even better than New York.

Just walk down North Michigan Avenue.  Mag Mile is always worth it - walk from Randolph north to the top of Michigan where Bloomies is.  Get pizza either at Due's or Malnatis.  Have high tea at the Intercontinental.  Go to the Art Instutite.  I miss Chicago sometimes....

message: This monkey wants a grape. "A similar lesson emerges from a classic experiment conducted by Franz de Waals and Sarah Brosnan. The primatologists trained brown capuchin monkeys to give them pebbles in exchange for cucumbers. Almost overnight, a capuchin economy developed, with hungry monkeys harvesting small stones. But the marketplace was disrupted when the scientists got mischievous: instead of giving every monkey a cucumber in exchange for pebbles, they started giving some monkeys a tasty grape instead. (Monkeys prefer grapes to cucumbers.) After witnessing this injustice, the monkeys earning cucumbers went on strike. Some started throwing their cucumbers at the scientists; the vast majority just stopped collecting pebbles. The capuchin economy ground to a halt. The monkeys were willing to forfeit cheap food simply to register their anger at the arbitrary pay scale."

message: Hmm.  So it is NOT OK for Internet backbone providers to cut deals with content providers to have their content served in "the fast lane", but it's OK for Google to do so.
name: Google to speed up, host customers' Web sites
caption: news.cnet.com
description: With its new Page Speed Service, Google will rewrite your Web page and host it on its own servers. Unlike previous efforts to speed the Web, this one isn't free. Read this blog post by Stephen Shankland on Deep Tech.

data.message: It doesn't appear the QoS on the network traffic is the fast lane factor. Rather, it is Google's massive connections to the rest of the internet and its ability to replicate content across servers to minimize hop counts when serving up the web pages. Not a bad idea for them to be in the hosting business. MS could do the same... :)

I might also add that it the service appears to only be suitable for largely static content... So you're typical restaurant web site menu page, etc. Not sure what happens for interactive pages... I suppose you're routed back to the "real" web site (Google acts as a Proxy Server).
it's the same as akami-type approach, no? very different from the QoS/DDoS approach of comcast, etc.

There are Internet access providers and then there is everyone else.  NetNeu is all about making sure the concepts of "common carriage" apply to access providers.   Analogous to Interstate Commerce Act of 1887 for the railroads.
@peter:  Agree.  I dont want the Internet to be like cable tv.  I don't want to be at the mercy of my provider to decide whether or not I can get access to sites/content/channels like Logo.

Matt Hargett Similar.  My view is that it is about how much influence and control you have over the medium.  Google has a large amount, but not enough to prevent choices. If they eventually dominate too much, then it could be a problem.

message: ...and so are you if you live solely in a top to bottom ecosystem that is controlled by a single company.  I don't.
name: Editorial: Apple's officially over the optical drive, for better or worse
caption: www.engadget.com
description: Engadget

data.message: Good riddance. Haven't used one in ~3 years.
I so rarely use the optical drive on my laptop that I kind of hope they get rid of them on the Pros before I go buy my new one. I'll be glad for the lighter machine.
...it's also worth noting that everyone bitched and pissed and moaned when Apple did away with the floppy drive. They led the industry on that one. They're doing the same here.

Yup.  the article examines that.  As long as Apple makes decisions that you do like, then there isn't a problem with 'benevolent dictator'.  However when they do, then it isn't.  Inevitably that happens.  A similar thing is going on right with batteries. After Apple made mac batteries non-removable, 3rd party external batteries started showing up.  Now Apple is suing them.  Apple wont let them use the mac connector to make external batteries that plug into the mac.
If you're worried about it, don't buy Apple stuff. For those of us who like Apple's products, and think they're making smart decisions, we'll happily remain a year or two ahead of the rest of you.

Hmm.  It seems to me that being "ahead" in this case has more downsides than upsides.  While I could agree that the need for an ODD is trending downward, and that need will eventually fall below the threshold that I don't need one, that is still in the future.  So in the present, while it may please my ego to be "ahead of the rest", my practical side would suffer some degree of pain for not having one when I need it. 

I also like that when I bought my thinkpad, I got to choose what populated the device bay: an extra battery pack, an ODD, an extra HDD, etc.  It's the additional degree of user choice and smaller degree of control I am forced to live under.

I also wouldnt want to live without my docking station.  (another apple no-no).  
That said, I don't have a problem buying apple products for certain categories.  Laptop or Computer, No.  But for a phone or tablet, I'm ok with it.
So glad you approve. :P

Also... you have choice with Apple products as well. Buy one or don't. My practical side says I almost never use my optical drive now, and when I do it's not the only way to solve the problem. All this griping about products you don't now, and never had any intention of owning. So silly. :P

This is hardly "benevolent dictator." They've made a product decision. If you want a computer with an optical drive, buy an external one or buy a non-Apple computer. It's not like they're remotely disabling all optical drives in computers people have already purchased.

Benevolent dictator with Apple is when they do things like change the iPhone Developer Agreement in ways that effect developers' livelihoods after they've already built their business on the iPhone platform. That's a situation where customers (in this case developers) are actually locked in and subject to the whims of Apple.
@Marc: Sure it is.  One company (er, one person) controls the whole hardware ecosystem. Steve Jobs decides what kinds of peripherals you can buy for Mac, whether those are from apple or acme.

@Josh: I think that's a gross exaggeration to say he controls the whole hardware ecosystem. Sure he has a large influence on where it goes because he controls a significant *minority* of the hardware marketplace with his company and makes important decisions and investments regarding what technologies win and lose with Apple. But he doesn't control the whole hardware ecosystem. Optical drives have been on their way out for years now. And you can blame the internet for that, not Steve Jobs.

So, you're telling me Dell doesn't control their whole hardware ecosystem? Everything Dell builds, they make design decisions about. HP, Asus, Acer... That they're all more risk-averse somehow makes them superior to a company that isn't?

@Adam, sure, there's degrees of lock-in all around.  However, it's the degree not the principle that is what causes pain. In the laptop/desktopserver market, there is a high degree of choice (within the windows world at least).  Mac is much more constrained.  If Dell tells me no more embedded ODD, I can go to a ThinkPad or HP.  If I want to run MacOS, I'm stuck.  I have to make my OS and HW decision together.  I can mix and match in the Windows world.

Marc Love  When I said "whole" I meant the whole Mac (or MacOS) based ecosystem.  There are no other legal MacOS HW systems except Apple's.  So certainly for the those types of things you are stuck with what Apple decides to build and you can't get a different MacOS machine from Dell or others.

And if that's important to you, you should stay in the Windows world. For many people, though, that's not a shared value, and the benefits of buying an Apple make up for the constraints. For instance, I know when I buy a Mac, it's not going to be loaded with bloatware from the hardware manufacturer that can't be removed without a computer science degree.

...  even worse, Apple's control goes beyond what they themselves build.  I'm fine if they don't want to build an external battery that can connect directly to the Apple magsafe connector.  Fine. 
 But to step in and prevent a third party that wants to meet customer demand by building such a product just because Apple says so?

@Josh: Apple users have been aware of that situation for years. It's the trade off we chose when chose the platform. Better overall experience in exchange for letting Apple make more decisions and giving us less options. If Apple starts fucking up, people can still make the transition back to PC's. Although granted going back won't be as easy. ;-)
Fortunately, being stuck with what Apple decides to build usually means top notch product engineering and support.

I'm actually looking forward to not having an optical drive. I think it's a good design decision... it's a choice I'd likely have made a long time ago considering the degree to which I never use my optical drive but still am forced to carry it around (as I would be on just about any OEM Windows laptop).

Josh Cohen I thought I might care about that when I made the switch from Microsoft-based systems to OSX-based systems, and in the last 4 years, I have never once felt constrained in my choices. I just don't need that much choice. And the benefits I get from the Apple ecosystem are huge.
Also, Cohen, don't you know by now there's no convincing me once I've made up my mind? ;P
LOL @ Adam

Marc Love You just hit the nail on the head.  It's a trade-off that a lot of people are happy with.  (~10% of the market)   They cede control and enjoy the benefits.  My comment is that the timing of when to move off of a given technology and migrate, such as away from ODD, is not something you can decide on your own.   

The control issue is broader than just MacOS, I'm frustrated by Apple's control in many areas.  
However, for a phone, I've made a similar choice.  When I bought my last phone, I wanted a tool not a science project, so I chose iPhone over Android.

message: Will apple continue doing design (as in A4) but have Build them or will they just reuse Intel-built chips?
name: Intel to Build Next Generation Processor for iOS devices? | WinBeta
caption: www.winbeta.org
description: It looks like Apple will be using Intel as a main processor manufacturer to power the iPad, iPod touch, and the iPhone. Apple, who currently uses Samsung, will focus on making a switch to Intel within a year.

data.message: The EETimes story is _much_ more tentative than the winbeta story that is based on it.
got a link?  What's your read on it?

They will not be switching to Intel unless Intel. They bought an entire custom chip house last year, why on earth would they switch away from the core competency of the talent they just purchased for millions of dollars?

Also, Intel has yet to produce a chip that comes close to the ARM Cortex, on which the A4/A5 series is based, in terms of performance, cost and power consumption.

So, unless Intel is custom manufacturing chips for Apple - like Samsung is now - this article is just speculation and perhaps some wishful thinking.
@jerame agreed.

@Josh - I know Intel really wants that business, so perhaps they planted this piece to generate some buzz and prop up their stock price or something.

I just don't see any logical reason for Apple to switch. You don't fix what isn't broken and the A4/A5 chips are absolutely phenomenal.

I mean, maybe they've hit an engineering roadblock for the A6, but I'm doubtful. Their chip guys are probably just now getting settled in and ramping up to speed on design. The A4 was a custom design before they bought that firm (I can't remember their name right now - grr) and the A5 is the first one any of those engineers even touched.

So, like I said before, I don't see why Apple would spend millions to purchase their talent, then totally change directions. Makes absolutely no sense

But anyone not really up on the ins and outs of this stuff could easily fall for it and buy some Intel stock based on the speculation. Maybe the author has some stock to offload and wants to get a good price.
EETimes story: http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4215650/Intel-vying-for-Apple-foundry-business-
"Foundry" means custom-manufactured....
My take is that Apple doesn't like a single source of supply any better than other IHVs do.  They can get ARMs built anywhere.
Smartest thing I've read on this whole issue: http://arstechnica.com/business/news/2011/05/intel-to-fab-arm-chips-for-apple-its-possible.ars?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=rss

message: I started with an Atari 830 Acoustic modem and then got a Hayes Smartmodem 300 for my Bar Mitzvah. w00t
name: A history of modems: 60 years of going online
caption: www.infoworld.com
description: This visual guide to the history of the modem takes you from the first models of the 1950s to today's machines

data.message: Tell me your modemular history

Lets see....  I started with a 300 baud VICmodem for my VIC20, and ran up a huge compuserve & Dow Jones bill with it... (mostly the former, on chat, go figure).  I would eventually get a C=64 1200 baud modem which sufficed for my basic university VAX connectivity, though the load of running it on my 64's motherboard seemed to cause heat-related intermittent failures, culminating in its SID chip ceasing to function.  For the next school year, I got an Amiga 500, with a no-name 2400 baud modem, which albeit a no-name, was immune to power fluctuations and line-noise that would knock every other modem off of the bank I'd be dialed into. (handy when modem banks were over-subscribed).  I ran with that setup (JRComm and the 2400) for over 2 years, until when asked by several friends what I wanted for my birthday, I asked for a 9600 baud modem, which they all pooled together and got me a fairly decent one, not USR, but whose name escapes me.  I would use this for another 2 or 3 years until 1995 when I went to work for ANS, and they had a few 14.4s kicking around that worked fine with Telix on the IBM pc they'd loaned me (the Amiga remained in Halifax).  By 1996 got a used Acer with a 28.8 internal that Linux Slackware recognized, and continued to use that until '97, when I moved to SF, and my roommate had an ISDN network.  In '99, I bought a house and a fully loaded Gateway, and cable modem service to ISPChannel.  ISPChannel would eventually go out of business, and @Home would serve San Bruno for a year before going tits-up themselves, whereupon I was asked to come in and do a contingency plan for them, which worked out rather well for both of us until my hiring director retired, and the new director and I didn't see eye-to-eye.

message: New 50mb wideband cable Internet. Linksys e3000 router meh.  Souped up with new DDWRT firmware. Rockin. Separate 5ghz channel,  no congestion. 50mb throughput over 802.11 A.

data.message: Huh?
Geeky stuff. I loaded a free alternative firmware for my router that has lots more features and stability.
50mb?!?!?! Wow dude, you are ready to host a ton of users on that. Or lots of porn. lol
If only Time Warner could run respectable DNS service.  The through put is super fast, but the DNS latency is so slow that requests intermittently fail.  Grrrrr!
Yeah or 8.8.4.4. That or opendns doesn't solve it.  It's like TW has something that is disturbing traffic on port 53

the best solution i found is to use a 2nd router.  The TW box is a modem/switch/wifi router.  I have a linksys e3000 plugged into that.  The e3 runs ddwrt with a DNS cache on it, which is pointed to opendns and google dns.  So, after any machines on my network access a site, DNS lookups are fast (cached).  I dunno, i may downgrade to the 20mb roadrunner service which doesnt seem to have that problem.
DD-WRT is a step in the right direction! Apple is 50% FOSS. The rest, they screw up ;-) I'm trying to speed up the Linux world; progress is steady but slow. And MS evolves.
Hmm, if you had a GNU/Linux'ish box at home (or a Mac) you could perhaps run a simple TinyDNS cache instead. Non-cache will still be an issue, I guess.
The router is running Linux. DDWRT is an embedded build. I can wear my pocket protector while I SSH in and be a real Linux haxx0r'
Yeah, I have played with DDWRT, but to be honest, never found it worth the trouble. YMMV, of course.
It *is* a hassle to get right.  Selecting the right build.  The initial flash needs to be one type of build then upgrades to that another.  Still some builds just work better than others.

I hope that embedded hardware will come with Linux by default at some point. I am more concerned about the desktop install. If you can't install DD-WRT, you probably shouldn't be running it. I am glad Linksys allows it. Apple has locked out Rockbox in their newer iPod hardware.

It's not so much that "you can't install" it.  The install is very easy.  You just use the router's web admin "firmware upgrade" page.  You just point it at the bin file on your local disk and click "upgrade". Then it uploads the file, installs it, then reboots the router.  The biggest complexity is finding the right build to install from the DDWRT site.  too many types and versions of the builds.  Each one seems to come with it's feature fixes and bugs.
Re: Linux desktop install, why not just get a mac?  All my linux friends have migrated to mac.  You get a reliable tool with great app support as well as a (mostly) real unix system underneath.

I love Linux and think it is superior to the Mac in many ways. I was just speaking about how the install needs work for world domination. Here are some of the things I wrote in my book for why the Mac sucks:




* A Mac OS has more code than ever before, and a lot of it is based on free code, but it doesn’t have a repository with thousands of applications like Linux. There are several third-party efforts to provide this feature, but none are blessed or supported by Apple. The Mac comes free with iPhoto, but they really want me to buy Aperture for $159, which they tell me just added 100 new features! Apple ships a new OS every year, but you don’t get free upgrades — it costs $140 to upgrade from OS X 10.4 to 10.5.



* Many of the Mac’s UI details like how to maximize windows, and shortcut keys, are dis-similar from Windows. Linux, by contrast, feels much more natural to a Windows user. Another example: when you double-click on a picture, it loads the iPreview application that stays around even after the window displaying the picture is closed. How about just creating a window, putting the picture in that window, and having it all disappear when I close the window? I tried to change the shortcuts to match the Windows keystrokes, but their software contains bugs because it didn’t change it in all applications.



* The Mac feels like a lot of disparate pieces bolted together. The desktop widgets code has its own UI, and it doesn’t integrate well into the OS desktop. The Spaces is a clone of an old Unix feature and doesn’t implement it as well as Linux does. (For example, there is no easily discoverable way to move applications between spaces.)



* As mentioned above, the Mac doesn’t support as many of the Microsoft standards as Linux does. One of the most obvious is WMA, but it also doesn’t ship with any software that reads and writes DOC files, even though there is OpenOffice.org and other free software out there.



* It is less customizable. I cannot find a way to have the computer not go to sleep when the laptop screen is closed. The mouse speed seems too slow and you can only adjust the amount of acceleration, not the sensitivity. You neither resize the system menu bar, nor add applets like you can with Linux’s Gnome.

data.message: I'm not surprised people are having problems with it. But I do have to say many of the specific complaints seem a little naive to me. They are issues you are going to have with ANY scalable system whether you write it from scratch on raw-hardware or not. For example- Memcached values can't be bigger than 1MB. You are stuffing more than 1MB in a SINGLE value? That would createa  huge crippling overhead on the datacenter network running your app if you are retrieving multiple MBs of cached data on every request.
(I should clarify- by "you" I mean the author, not actually _you_) :)

Yeah I read the article previously and just didn't buy most of its arguments. GAE has a specific design and it's quite clear about its limitations. So if you are a round peg, it's a round hole. This guy was a square peg. Nevertheless he is exactly the kind of customer that would do well on Azure. :)

data.message:
HST not LBJ of course. The blog made the error initially.

A major difference is the prior to Truman's executive order, African American service members were already serving. Segregated units had to be integrated. This caused the military to take real action to reorganize many units.

With DADT the military only needs to stop taking adverse actions against service members. No administratve or reorganizatioal action is needed.

I see your point.  However, while the issues that need to get resolved during are different, I beleive there are still issues that will need to get resolved.  There are folks in the services who will have issues serving with gay people.  Whether we agree about the validity of those issues, they still need to be addressed.  Having homophobes with guns running around scares me.  I'm worried that there might be fragging incidents.  Identifying problematic servicemen and giving them diversity training or perhaps removing them from the situation might be necessary.

Race was far more divisive when Truman signed that order. Nationally, repeal of DADT has support of 75%. For younger people, it is higher. Most service members are younger, and much less homophobic than the brass. They are far, far, less homophobic than the troops in Truman's day were racist. 

Military codes of conduct are quite sufficient to handle this as is.

message: incrememtalism in healthcare
name: Op-Ed Columnist - Tidings of Comfort - NYTimes.com
caption: www.nytimes.com
description: Imperfect as it is, the health care reform bill, which will likely become a law, will make America a better country.

data.message: Will it be improved over time, or weakened?
Hmm.  well, i guess that depends on who gets elected.  Though the current bull is so far from what we were hoping for, it's painful to imagine it getting weakened.
Painful to imagine, yes.  But likely, given the controlling influence of big money.
Incrementally backward, actually.  The right solution would have enabled health insurers to work cross state lines; without that, we've got monopolies, high premiums, and reduced benefits.
Um, the Senate bill does allow insurance to be sold across state lines.  That's one of the major flaws, as it eliminates protections that some states offer.  Like Delaware for credit cards.
The bill should have government-provided basic coverage, with anyone and any company free to purchase additional coverage.  No mandates, no middlemen, no overhead.

Randall - we'll see how it plays out when merged reconciled with the House.  Gov't insurance has vastly more overhead than private insurance.  You should read up on Medicare overhead and particularly fraud.   Prior to Obama's spending spree this year,  Medicare has been traditionally one of the two largest single federal line items - at about 25% of total US spending annually.  You think covering 20% of Americans (healthcare only) is efficiently covered by 25% of the TOTAL Federal budget?  Strange.  And we didn't even discuss Medicaid or the other gov't run healthcare programs that already exist.

message: Obama's High Crimes: Being Black
name: Poll: 35% Of Republicans Want To Impeach Obama
caption: www.huffingtonpost.com
description: A new poll released by Public Policy Polling Wednesday introduced some surprising numbers.

data.message: There isn't really anything to impeach him for, but his performance has been mind-numbingly awful.  If I could go change my vote, McCain would have it.
If the Republicans had nominated a white constitutional law professor, the media would have slammed him as a clueless elite out of touch with reality. Obama got a different treatment.

I have low expectations from our government no matter who's in charge.  However, I'm content enough, at this early stage in Obama's first term, with the progress on issues and unwinding some of the messes he inherited.  Among other things, we're actually having a health care reform debate, we've started actually talking to folks like Iran instead of provoking them "Axis of Evil!", the Matthew Shepard federal hate crimes law has been signed into law, the legislature is moving forward to give domestic partner benefits to govt employees...  I don't believe these things would be happening if McCain was elected.

The best way to be happy with Obama is to lower your expectations. If "having a healthcare debate" is more important than "passing legislation that will lower costs and improve quality", then you can be satisfied with the progress.

The Republican party's best community organizer is Obama!

WIth Obama, at least things are moving in the right direction.  The meat of the bill is ultimately negotiated by the legislature, so the efficacy of the final bill is more than just his responsibility.  I would expect that health care reform, especially given people's strong feelings on it, will take a big chunk of time to come to agreement on in order to pass something into law.  The President sets the agenda, and I like what he's doing.
You sound more interested in intentions than results.
why?

Because you speak of "hard feelings" rather than "good policies." And you say it is fine that Obama is delegating the details of the legislation to Congress.

You either don't care about whether the effort will achieve the announced goals, or you know the results won't be good, so are choosing to ignore that aspect.

The only bipartisanship in DC is in opposition to Obama's policies! McCain would do better, as Bush did.

Josh, Check this out.  http://www.gpoaccess.gov/usbudget/fy10/pdf/budget/summary.pdf

Bush was a bad spender - he racked up a $459B deficit.  In this document (prepared by the Obama administration!)  Obama states pulicly that he is planning to rack up deficits of $1,509B this year, $1,178B next year, then $1,033B, $757B, $734B, $791B, $811B, $878B, and upward from there....  In other words, on a GOOD year, Obama is 2x WORSE than Bush!

This is gross financial irresponsibility.  This isn't just TARP.  This is pure Obama.  

At the same time, if he gets his way, the economy will be slammed with the single biggest tax increase ever! (healthcare)

At the same time, he wants to deal with climate change, that is good.  But is he really planning to pay for the chinese to clean up their act?  The only tax increase bigger than healthcare could be this one!

But what about an energy policy?  Does Obama have a plan?  Nope.  How about job growth, do we have that?  Nope!

How about getting us out of the middle east?  Is he doing that?  Nope!  Shit - that was the reason I voted for him!  He wants to do Bush-round-2, this time in Afghanistan.

Obama is a total disaster of financial irresponsibility, forgotten promises, and not even addressing our nation's basic needs.

Mike, I'm impressed with your open-mindedness.

Many people are Democrats first and Americans second  and get so caught up in wanting to believe in Obama that they rationalize even his bad decisions. It is a sad pseudo-religion with Obama as the Messiah.

Wasn't Tiger Woods the model of a perfect family man until 2 weeks ago? The image of Obama was equally as whitewashed.

message: Why we need Hate Crimes legislation
name: The Bilerico Project | Why Attack Gays? Killer: They Are Easy Targets
caption: www.bilerico.com
description: Editors' Note: Guest blogger Josh Cohen has been doing various types of LGBT activism for roughly 15 years. Originally from New Jersey (Exit 9), he began his activism at college, staging somewhat militant events on campus. ...

data.message: Sure, I get it.  Some people kill because they hate some group.  The guy is in jail for 20yrs, which seems pretty appropriate to me.  Why do we need hate crime legislation?  He's already in jail.  The system worked.  Whether he kills because he hates, because his targets are easy, because he's violent, because he's stupid, or all of the above, the law worked.   I don't really care if we have hate legislation or not.  If it makes some groups of people feel better to have it, then I'm not really against it either, but to me it's just redundant law.
Hmmm, don't really mean I like that "gays are easy targets:. Sounds kind of morbid. I support calling out this issue. =)

@Mike:  I think hate crimes are different b/c they're not just crimes against an individual, they are also attacking a whole group of people.  e.g., after 9/11 people attacked Muslims, or even just people who appeared to be Muslims.  That hurt all Muslims, in addition to the people who were actually attacked.  The other Muslims weren't harmed in the same way of course, but they were still harmed.  At least, that's my view. :)

What is the theory and framework of justice? Retributive? Is the choice of penalty based on its value as a deterrent? If the idea is to impose punishment calibrated to societal moral codes and goals a hate crime ranks higher on the negative scale than say a crime of passion. Society then decides that the punishment has to fit the extent to which the perpetrator is found immoral. I am not saying I endorse such a framework, but I can see the validity of such a justification. The law does take intent into account in various instances.

yeah, exactly -- motive counts.  and if someone says "I killed him b/c he was gay" or some such, it's pretty easy to figure out motive.  it doesn't distinguish victims -- not every murder of someone who happens to be gay is a hate crime.

@Mike: Why do we make a distinction between first degree murder and manslaughter?  Because the former is more likely to be repeated, thus a more serious punishment is merited.  A criminal who commits a hate crime is likely to repeat that crime on someone else in the target class in the future.  So again, that means the punishment should be more serious to protect society.

@Chris - First degree vs Second degree murder already covers hate motives as well as other motives.  I never said we shouldn't consider motive, we absolutely should, and we already do.  Hate crime legislation is redundant with existing law.  As Keith also intelligently pointed out, Hate Crime legislation gives some victims less justice than others, which is wrong.  It is not more serious to kill homosexual people than heterosexual people.

@mike:  " It is not more serious to kill homosexual people than heterosexual people."
Sure, if you throw a rock in the air and it kills a gay, heterosexual, christian, black person, or woman, its all the same.
However, if you seek out someone because they are a member of a certain persecuted group, it is more serious.  You're not really attacking that person, or even based on your own passion for that persion.  You're attacking a protected class of people.  
In both the case i describe as well as the Matt Shepard case, they were selected because they were gay.  in both cases, the killers cited the victims sexuaity and an alledged sexual advance as a motive for their murder.

I can understand the libertarian view that the government shouldnt be imposing laws like this.  However, consider that whats happening here is that LGBT is being aded to an existing list of protected classes.  So, being opposed to any hate crimes laws is a reasonable position (though its not one i share; i be

hmm is there a limit on length here or am i just hitting some IE8 bug?  
Continuing:
So, being opposed to any hate crimes laws is a reasonable position (though its not one i share; i believe they are necesary).  However, whats going on here is the inclusion of LGBT in an existing model.

assuming that we *do* have hate crimes laws, are you oppsed to adding LGBT alongside, race, sex, religion, etc?

It isn't clear that federal hate crime legislation already exists. I found a quote from star tribune:

"The legislation, also known as the Matthew Shepard Act, would assist federal officials in their prosecution of hate crimes that target victims because of race, color, religion, national origin, gender, sexual orientation, sexual identity or disability."

@josh: I don't trust wikipedia when it comes to politics. And when I click on the link for HR 1592, it mentions many more categories of hate crimes.

I googled some more and found that HRC agrees with me!

http://www.hrc.org/laws_and_elections/5660.htm

BTW, I find it Orwellian that the law is named after someone whose perps received life sentences!
BTW, I find it Orwellian that the law is named after someone whose perps received life sentences!

description: Rules: Once you've been tagged, you are supposed to write a note with 25 random things, facts, habits, or goals about you. At the end, choose 25 people to be tagged. You have to tag the person who tag

data.message: #14 explains Brian. He laughs more than anyone I have ever met. Thanks for the warning on #11. I'll make sure to never pay you a surprise visit. ;-)

I bet they will now.. HA!
#26.  Old friends that have been out of touch still consider me one of their all time favorite people....

It gave me up when the muffler went and later the radiator.  I was going to give it to charity but oddly enough a friend bought it from me and fixed it up and drove it another year or so before it finally died.  I upgraded from the Storm to a BMW....so I really need to keep this car for at least twice as long as the storm.
Wasn't that storm a magnet for breakins in new brunswick?

back atcha Nikki....you are one of the people whose laugh I found infectious.  I miss the days of sitting on the porch on Freeman St in NB drinking coffee with whipped cream and smoking cigs....also miss the poker games and trips to Oz bar in NB on Wednesdays (My boss at IBM always wondered why I came into work so late on Thurs morns).
With no driver's side window on the storm for a long time, not really a break-in....just reach in and take what you want.  That and the cat who lived in it when it was parked on the street.
at roughly 5K miles a year, I should be able to get my money's worth on it.  And that included a road trip from Atlanta to Maine to Quebec to Toronto to Pittsburg and back to Atlanta.
Couldn't you have been more OCD when we lived together?  Like doing dishes???  and I seem to recall one time they dumped everything out of your glove compartment and didn't take a thing!!!

Nothing to take....The best was when a fight broke out in front of the house and someone got thrown up on my car, denting the hood with their body and cracking the windshield with their head.  The blood got cleaned off quickly but it took me a few years to replace the windshield.
I seem to recall you driving on 287 in a snow storm...with no ability to see out of the windshield...and no driver side window!!
Good times.

Yea....the driver's side window got broken when I was working for Will Lloyd as a laborer.  Someone backed into my parked car when the window was down so it got broken.  She had no insurance so I agreed to just let her pay me and she never did.  I was too poor (read cheap) for a long time to fix it and had to bundle up for the long drive from NB to IBM in Parsippany in the winter.  It finally got fixed when I moved to Atlanta but the windshield stayed cracked for another few years.  The worst was when I got into an accident on 287 heading to work and the airbag deployed.  I had just opened my "Big One" Dunkin Donuts coffee so I ended up with hot coffee burns all over me.  And the airbag never got replaced.  I just folded it back up and tucked it into the steerin wheel an glued the steering wheel back shut.   Good times indeed!
Damn... Cheap doesn't do you justice.. LOL

I'm stealthy.  :-P
